answers.body_markdown:
In GraphQL we don&#39;t have union type as you described.

The best alternative I can think of is something like this:

    type User
      id: ID!
      name: String!
      userTypes: [UserType]
    }
    
    type UserType {
       teacher: TeacherType
       user: UserType
    }
    
    type TeacherType{
       id:String
       name:String
       subjectsTaught:String
    }
    
    type UserType{
       id:String
       name:String
       lessons:String
    }

You can use Union in graphQL Queries(https://graphql.org/learn/schema/) and (https://www.apollographql.com/docs/apollo-server/schema/unions-interfaces/)

However the issue is *input Unions* are not supported for Mutations. Specifically, this section of code is correct 

    userTypes {
      ... on Teacher {
        id
        name
        subjectsTaught
      }
      ... on Student {
        id
        name
        lessons
      }
    }

What I believe is not working for you is the following code section because you are trying to pass a *Union* in as an input. A Mutation cannot take a union as an input.

    `mutation RegisterUser($input: CreateUserInput!) { registerUser(input: $input){...}



Mutations can only take Scalar types or a special type called *Input*, which can be a mapped object but all of the internal fields **have to be** Scalar types.

So you cannot use Unions for Mutations. In fact, I don&#39;t agree with the example from LxL, you should separate your mutation schema defined types to all be *Input* type, and then use the Union for querying. 

A potential solution to this is to use an Enum type for Teacher/Student and flatten the types into one *Input* type and then handle the difference in the resolver if there are different fields.

